ella pneumophila","Haemophilus influenzae"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral respiratory pathogens have evolved mechanisms to survive within host cells, particularly alveolar macrophages. \u003Cstrong\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E is an extracellular pathogen that adheres to respiratory epithelium. \u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E is also an extracellular pathogen that causes damage through toxin production. \u003Cstrong\u003EChlamydophila pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E can infect respiratory epithelial cells but not typically macrophages. \u003Cstrong\u003ELegionella pneumophila\u003C/strong\u003E is an intracellular pathogen that can survive and multiply within alveolar macrophages by preventing phagosome-lysosome fusion. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/strong\u003E is an extracellular pathogen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intracellular pathogens can survive within alveolar macrophages by evading phagocytic destruction","Key respiratory pathogens that can survive inside macrophages include Mycobacterium tuberculosis, Legionella pneumophila, and Chlamydophila pneumoniae"],"references":["Viasus D, Gaia V, Manzur-Barbur C, Carratal\u00e0 J. Legionnaires\u0027 Disease: Update on Diagnosis and Treatment. Infect Dis Ther. 2022 Jun;11(3):973-986. doi: 10.1007/s40121-022-00635-7. Epub 2022 May 3. PMID: 35505000; PMCID: PMC9124264.","Cunha BA, Burillo A, Bouza E. Legionnaires\u0027 disease. Lancet. 2016 Jan 23;387(10016):376-385. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)60078-2. Epub 2015 Jul 28. PMID: 26231463.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Healt